×031Gameboy   Scene   ,   Results
=============================×
Only  the  hardware limitations, the scene-people are
the   same.

Unlike  amiga,  gameboy  is usually the 2nd platform.
The  sceners  are  mainly from speccy or c64 and only
make one or two demos. At the moment there's very few
people  who  are  active,  and  not  much interaction
between   them.

Amiga   scene   is   1000   times   bigger.

Biggest difference is that the Amiga scene is an OPEN
scene.  You have dozens of legal tools and it is much
easier  to  get system information, while the Gameboy
is  a  complete closed system which had to be reverse
engineering  first.  The  Gamboy-Scene in relation to
the   Amiga-Scene   is   a   very   young   one.

It's  very  nice to watch demos on the subway and the
scene  has  sure matured with GBA, but it still lacks
the   mileage   the   Amiga   has

It  seems  like  Amiga had their turning point around
the  year  1998.  I don't want to say that it's going
downwards  yet.  While  for the Gameboy scene it's an
upgoing   curve.

Amiga  sceners  think they're doing serious stuff for
real   computers

Gameboy  classic  /  color  scene  seems to be almost
non-existing.  The scene on the Gameboy Advance seems
